body:
There is a bug in `ResolveTraces` where it is hard-coding the final target names. This causes problems for situations where `LowerTypes` introduces name conflicts.

Consider:

```
circuit Foo: %[[
  {
    "class":"chisel3.experimental.Trace$TraceNameAnnotation",
    "target":"~Foo|Foo>a_0",
    "chiselTarget":"ground"
  },
  {
    "class":"chisel3.experimental.Trace$TraceNameAnnotation",
    "target":"~Foo|Foo>a[0]",
    "chiselTarget":"vector"
  }
]]
  module Foo:
    input a: UInt<1>[1]
    input a_0: UInt<1>
```

Currently this compiles to:

```verilog
// Generated by CIRCT unknown git version
module Foo(
  input a_0,
        a_0_0
);

endmodule
```

```json
[
  {
    "class": "chisel3.experimental.Trace$TraceAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Foo>a_0",
    "chiselTarget": "ground"
  },
  {
    "class": "chisel3.experimental.Trace$TraceAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Foo>a_0",
    "chiselTarget": "vector"
  }
]
```

This should be a relatively straightforward fix of using verbatim substitutions.
